04387nam a22006615i 9780226458588DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016051250  a9780226458588  a(DE-B1597)524622  a(OCoLC)993878555  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN751b.G65 2017 4aPN1083.S43 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.1936090342231 aGoldstein, Amanda Jo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSweet Science :bRomantic Materialism and the New Logics of Life /cAmanda Jo Goldstein. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b6 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: “Sweet Science” -- tChapter 1. Blake’s Mundane Egg: Epigenesis and Milieux -- tChapter 2. Equivocal Life: Goethe’s Journals on Morphology -- tChapter 3. Tender Semiosis: Reading Goethe with Lucretius and Paul de Man -- tChapter 4. Growing Old Together: Lucretian Materialism in Shelley’s The Triumph of Life -- tChapter 5. A Natural History of Violence: Allegory and Atomism in Shelley’s The Mask of Anarchy -- tCoda: Old Materialism, or Romantic Marx -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday we do not expect poems to carry scientifically valid information. But it was not always so. In Sweet Science, Amanda Jo Goldstein returns to the beginnings of the division of labor between literature and science to recover a tradition of Romantic life writing for which poetry was a privileged technique of empirical inquiry. Goldstein puts apparently literary projects, such as William Blake’s poetry of embryogenesis, Goethe’s journals On Morphology, and Percy Shelley’s “poetry of life,” back into conversation with the openly poetic life sciences of Erasmus Darwin, J. G. Herder, Jean-Baptiste Lamarck, and Étienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire. Such poetic sciences, Goldstein argues, share in reviving Lucretius’s De rerum natura to advance a view of biological life as neither self-organized nor autonomous, but rather dependent on the collaborative and symbolic processes that give it viable and recognizable form. They summon De rerum natura for a logic of life resistant to the vitalist stress on self-authorizing power and to make a monumental case for poetry’s role in the perception and communication of empirical realities. The first dedicated study of this mortal and materialist dimension of Romantic biopoetics, Sweet Science opens a through-line between Enlightenment materialisms of nature and Marx’s coming historical materialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEuropean literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and science. 0aLucretius Carus, Titus - Influence. 0aMaterialism in literature. 0aRomanticism. 0aScience in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aJohann Wolfgang von Goethe.  aLucretius.  aPercy Shelley.  aRomanticism.  aWilliam Blake.  abiology.  aempiricism.  amaterialism.  apoetry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226458588423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226458588/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles